    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"321696\">Julian Berman</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/113489-new-members/topic/can't.20find.20an.20example.20of.20a.20mathlib.20definition.20of.20type.20.E2.84.95/near/485239636\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>That isn't of type <code>\\N</code>, it's of type <code>\\N \\to \\N</code>. Is that what you're looking for?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Is it the case that (1) you are strictly correct, but (2) people speaking informally are happy to refer to the output type as \"the type\" ?</p>\n<p>I'm just comparing to computer science where people refer to the output of a function as \"the type\" rather than the mathematical idea of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f:X \\to \\mathbb{N}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">N</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
